article.description:
Mwadi Mabika scored 24 points, Lisa Leslie
had 22 and 11 rebounds and the Los Angeles Sparks beat the Detroit
Shock 86-78 to win their home opener Wednesday night.

article.headline: Sparks hold off Shock in happy homecoming
article.linkText: Sparks welcome Holdsclaw, beat Shock in home opener
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Playing at home for the first time this
season was all Mwadi Mabika needed to break out of an offensive
slump.

Mabika scored 24 points, Lisa Leslie had 22 and 11 rebounds and
the Los Angeles Sparks beat the Detroit Shock 86-78 Wednesday
night.

"I just play well at home," Mabika said. "I'm so used to the
basketball and the rims."

Temeka Johnson added 19 points, six assists and six rebounds for
the Sparks, who had a 3-3 record in their first six games on the
road.

Ruth Riley led the Shock with 19 points -- one of five starters
in double figures.

"We have stages where we're standing around too much," she
said. "We're not finishing."

Mabika scored a combined 10 points in her last four games after
having 19 in a season-opening loss at Seattle.

She played 38½ minutes -- tops in the game. She missed two of her
nine field-goal attempts and made 7 of 8 free throws.

"I don't have to play 40," she said. "Put me in there the
first 10 minutes and see how I'm doing."

At one point, coach Joe Bryant asked Mabika how she was feeling.

"She said, `I'm a little tired," he said. "I said, `Not
tonight. You got to go 40 tonight."

Chamique Holdsclaw had 13 points off the bench in her first game
with the Sparks after missing the season's opening two weeks to be
with her father and stepfather, who both have cancer.

"With Chamique in the game, it makes it easy for everyone,"
Bryant said. "Taking Chamique away is like taking Kobe away from
the Lakers. You got to guard her and Mwadi gets more shots."

Holdsclaw made all five of her free throws playing just under 30
minutes.

"I'm just trying to get back into the rhythm," she said. "It
feels good just to be around the team again, the high-fives and the
excitement. I got that first one out of the way. I wasn't as tired
as I thought I would be."

The Sparks raced to an 18-9 lead in the first quarter before the
Shock rallied to tie the game and take a two-point lead. But Los
Angeles went back in front, helped by Johnson's jumper that banked
in just before the buzzer.

Detroit kept it close before getting within four early in the
third period. That's when the Sparks took over for good, outscoring
the Shock 21-16 in the quarter to lead 65-54 with 10 minutes
remaining. Leslie, Mabika and Johnson scored all but two of the
Sparks' points.

"I'm never worried about Mwadi when we get home," Leslie said.
"As much as she wants to shoot, I'll just keep screening. I don't
care."

Leslie and Johnson, a 5-foot-3 fireplug who fearlessly drove the
lane, controlled a stretch early in the fourth quarter with a
combined seven consecutive points that stretched the Sparks' lead
to 13.

"We have an intensity problem to deal with," Shock coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "We break down at times because we lose our
intensity. We couldn't match the energy they played with."

The Shock got within four on Swin Cash's fastbreak layin off
Johnson's turnover. But Holdsclaw scored three in a row and Los
Angeles hung on.

Bryant improved to 4-0 at home as Sparks coach since taking over
last season, when the team won its final three home games --
including his first WNBA victory against Detroit.
